  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the best books/Tutorials to learn C# for non-beginners programmers?",
  "response": "If you're already a programmer proficient in other languages and looking to learn C#, there are advanced resources that can help you quickly grasp the language's nuances and leverage your existing programming experience. Here are some highly recommended books and tutorials:\n\n### Books:\n\n1. **\"Pro C# 8 with .NET Core 3\" by Andrew Troelsen and Phillip Japikse**\n   - This book is a comprehensive guide to C# and the .NET Core framework. It covers advanced topics and is suitable for experienced programmers.\n\n2. **\"C# in Depth\" by Jon Skeet**\n   - This book delves deeper into the intricacies of the C# language, focusing on more advanced features. Jon Skeet is well-known in the programming community, and his insights are invaluable.\n\n3. **\"C# 7.0 in a Nutshell: The Definitive Reference\" by Joseph Albahari and Ben Albahari**\n   - Part of the well-known \"In a Nutshell\" series, this book is a thorough reference that can assist in learning more advanced topics in C#.\n\n4. **\"Programming C# 8.0: Build Cloud, Web, and Desktop Applications\" by Ian Griffiths**\n   - This book is focused on modern C# development, including cloud, web, and desktop applications, with coverage of advanced features in C# 8.0.\n\n5. **\"The C# Programming Yellow Book\" by Rob Miles**\n   - While more accessible, Rob Miles has a way of explaining complex topics in an approachable manner. The book covers intermediate to advanced topics.\n\n### Online Tutorials and Courses:\n\n1. **Pluralsight**\n   - Pluralsight offers high-quality video courses for intermediate and advanced C# developers. Look for courses on specific topics like \"Advanced C#\" or \"C# Design Patterns\".\n\n2. **Microsoft Learn**\n   - Microsoft Learn has a variety of modules and learning paths that cover advanced C# topics. It's a great way to get hands-on experience with the technology stack directly from Microsoft.\n\n3. **Udemy**\n   - Udemy has many courses tailored to different levels of expertise. Courses like \"Advanced C# Programming\" can be very helpful.\n\n4. **Coursera**\n   - Look for courses specifically focusing on C# and .NET, which often collate university-level material and professional teaching methods.\n\n5. **YouTube Channels like \"Tim Corey\" or \"dotNetConf\"**\n   - These channels have excellent content for intermediate and advanced C# developers. Tim Corey, for example, offers in-depth tutorials on various topics including advanced C# features and best practices.\n\n### Blogs and Online Articles:\n\n1. **C# Corner**\n   - A community-driven blog with articles ranging from beginner to advanced topics.\n\n2. **CodeProject**\n   - A hub of articles, tutorials, and code samples from developers around the world. Look for advanced topics specifically.\n\n3. **Stack Overflow**\n   - Not a tutorial site per se, but browsing questions and solutions on Stack Overflow can give insight into common problems and advanced techniques in C# programming.\n\nCombining these resources will provide a robust and comprehensive understanding of C# for someone who already has programming experience.",
